IT is hardly necessary to read Estre's summary of the many and mutually destructive theories that have been proposed in order to perceive the sutility of attempting to construet out of the Pyrrhas‚ Lalages‚ Lydias of the Odes a history of Horace's loves and disappointments. Whatever foundation any Ode may have had in the feelings or facts of the moment it is impossible now to distinguish shadow from substance3 and there is much to indicate that Horace did not wish it to be otherwise. XVhatever be their origin, he treats his love Odes as artistic studies. He arranges them not, we can feel sure, in any chronological order as remembrances of his own life, but where they will be most useful to relieve more serious poems or to stand side by side as companion pictures. We may see as much as this from the nature of the names which he employs. A certain number owe their selection obviously to their etymo- logical meaning, such as Pyrrha in 1. 5, Chloe in 1. 23, Lyce in 3. 10, Phidyle in 3. 23 (cp.
